WEBVTT

1
00:00:05.780 --> 00:00:09.520
So good afternoon, everyone. It is my pleasure to welcome

2
00:00:09.600 --> 00:00:13.100
you to this symposium on Inflammaging and Cancer: Mechanistic

3
00:00:13.220 --> 00:00:14.840
Insights and Therapeutic Opportunity.

4
00:00:15.820 --> 00:00:19.800
I am Olga Anchukov. I'm an associate professor and a program leader

5
00:00:19.840 --> 00:00:23.460
at our NCI-designated cancer center at The Jackson Laboratory.

6
00:00:24.820 --> 00:00:27.340
And so we're very excited to share.

7
00:00:27.980 --> 00:00:31.480
We have four speakers in this session that will share their latest research

8
00:00:32.119 --> 00:00:34.860
on the topics of aging, inflammation, and cancer.

9
00:00:35.940 --> 00:00:39.860
And as you probably appreciate, age is really one of the main risk factors

10
00:00:39.900 --> 00:00:43.060
for most adult cancers, with the incidence of

11
00:00:43.520 --> 00:00:47.089
many frequent cancer types, and especially solid tumors as

12
00:00:47.420 --> 00:00:50.940
well as leukemias, really skyrocketing in the

13
00:00:50.960 --> 00:00:54.840
population. And this is, of course, a problem as our population is aging

14
00:00:54.880 --> 00:00:58.769
faster. There is more and more cancer that are

15
00:00:58.800 --> 00:00:59.820
being detected.

16
00:01:01.940 --> 00:01:04.820
There are a number really of key

17
00:01:05.121 --> 00:01:09.100
similarities between the molecular and cellular pathways that are shared during

18
00:01:09.180 --> 00:01:12.660
aging and cancer, and many of the so-called cancer

19
00:01:12.760 --> 00:01:16.200
hallmarks are also overlapping with the aging hallmarks.

20
00:01:16.240 --> 00:01:19.780
The one that we're going to focus today and during the sessions is really the

21
00:01:19.860 --> 00:01:22.580
impact of aging and chronic inflammation.

22
00:01:23.960 --> 00:01:27.440
As you probably know, as we age, our immune system starts

23
00:01:28.200 --> 00:01:31.640
functioning less well. There's a lot of changes both in the

24
00:01:31.700 --> 00:01:35.460
immune cell composition as well as the activity

25
00:01:35.920 --> 00:01:37.880
across all different cell types.

26
00:01:38.760 --> 00:01:42.440
With age, we also see an increase of a

27
00:01:42.500 --> 00:01:46.200
number of processes that will lead to a so-called

28
00:01:46.260 --> 00:01:50.160
inflammaging. And so those include chronic low-grade

29
00:01:50.220 --> 00:01:54.000
inflammation over time that accumulates and triggers a

30
00:01:54.020 --> 00:01:57.950
number of cellular and molecular phenotypes, including the accumulation

31
00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:00.780
of senescence-associated secretory phenotypes,

32
00:02:01.300 --> 00:02:04.900
activation of cGAS-STING pathways, recognition of

33
00:02:05.880 --> 00:02:07.100
PAMPs and DAMPs,

34
00:02:08.100 --> 00:02:11.760
metabolic dysregulation, as well as

35
00:02:11.780 --> 00:02:14.860
many epigenetic and proteasomal changes.

36
00:02:15.280 --> 00:02:18.940
And all of this leads to secretion of a number of pro-inflammatory

37
00:02:19.020 --> 00:02:22.920
cytokine that keeps stimulating those processes, as well as

38
00:02:22.960 --> 00:02:25.000
many other molecular pathways.

39
00:02:26.380 --> 00:02:30.240
And so this immune dysfunction of age really has profound effects on

40
00:02:30.280 --> 00:02:31.980
cancer development and progression.

41
00:02:33.220 --> 00:02:36.520
As we age, differences in immune cell fitness

42
00:02:37.260 --> 00:02:41.120
really lead to differences in responses in the older

43
00:02:41.180 --> 00:02:44.900
population. Aging alters the immune repertoire, the immune

44
00:02:44.980 --> 00:02:48.940
microenvironment. Older cancer patients do not respond as well to

45
00:02:48.980 --> 00:02:52.700
therapy as younger patients. Yet the problem is that most of

46
00:02:52.740 --> 00:02:56.180
our current clinical trials are done in younger patients and are not

47
00:02:56.320 --> 00:03:00.000
adapted to an older immune

48
00:03:00.010 --> 00:03:00.820
environment.

49
00:03:02.020 --> 00:03:05.680
Also, another component of aging is that many of the cancer treatments

50
00:03:06.080 --> 00:03:09.800
that we're giving to patients actually accelerate aging of

51
00:03:09.840 --> 00:03:13.340
cancer survivors. And so this is another aspect of aging that is

52
00:03:13.400 --> 00:03:15.459
important to take into account.

53
00:03:16.820 --> 00:03:20.760
So there are a number of opportunities that are currently being explored to

54
00:03:20.820 --> 00:03:24.100
target inflammaging in the context of cancer, and many challenges.

55
00:03:25.600 --> 00:03:28.760
One avenue is really targeting

56
00:03:28.820 --> 00:03:32.540
senescence-associated sources and dampening the senescent

57
00:03:32.620 --> 00:03:36.580
secretome for the use, for example, of senolytic or senomorphics.

58
00:03:37.400 --> 00:03:40.420
The therapeutic windows still remains unclear.

59
00:03:40.940 --> 00:03:43.900
Another approach is modulation of cGAS-STING pathways.

60
00:03:44.560 --> 00:03:45.400
And again, here,

61
00:03:46.260 --> 00:03:50.200
really important is the context of how do you achieve the right

62
00:03:50.240 --> 00:03:53.780
balance between antitumor immunity and chronic activation.

63
00:03:55.100 --> 00:03:57.620
Inhibition of the IL-6 axis

64
00:03:58.160 --> 00:03:59.260
also

65
00:04:00.780 --> 00:04:04.480
has some rationale. Again, here is how do we find the right

66
00:04:04.580 --> 00:04:05.800
balance and the right

67
00:04:07.180 --> 00:04:10.420
modes of immunosuppression. And finally, a number of

68
00:04:10.960 --> 00:04:14.200
approaches are currently being exploited to try to reprogram

69
00:04:14.210 --> 00:04:16.240
metabolically senescent cells.

70
00:04:17.680 --> 00:04:21.360
And so as we hear the talks, we're going to have four short talks and hopefully a

71
00:04:21.380 --> 00:04:23.280
discussion at the end, and some of the things I

72
00:04:24.100 --> 00:04:27.440
think we would love to discuss is really how do we apply

73
00:04:28.220 --> 00:04:31.660
what we're learning about inflammaging and cancer to really advance clinical

74
00:04:31.740 --> 00:04:33.720
management as well as therapeutic development.

75
00:04:34.220 --> 00:04:37.580
One of the questions is how do we stratify better patients?

76
00:04:37.640 --> 00:04:39.680
Are there better clinical biomarkers?

77
00:04:40.500 --> 00:04:41.920
When do we need to intervene

78
00:04:42.760 --> 00:04:46.630
to have maximum efficacy? And what is the tissue specificity of

79
00:04:46.640 --> 00:04:48.590
some of those inflammaging programs?

80
00:04:49.940 --> 00:04:53.600
With such, I think there are a few things that we start needing to take into

81
00:04:53.640 --> 00:04:56.760
account better in our preclinical and clinical

82
00:04:57.600 --> 00:05:01.500
research. One is really measuring immune aging in both cancer models

83
00:05:01.540 --> 00:05:05.480
and cancer patients in a more systematic manner, integrating some of those

84
00:05:05.560 --> 00:05:08.940
aged models to design and test novel intervention strategy.

85
00:05:10.580 --> 00:05:14.320
Although the aging field has come up with a number of

86
00:05:14.360 --> 00:05:18.300
ways to measure biological aging, I think none of those have

87
00:05:18.320 --> 00:05:22.260
really been yet exploited in the context of oncology, so we

88
00:05:22.320 --> 00:05:24.539
don't know how they're applicable between

89
00:05:25.360 --> 00:05:27.060
older people and cancer patients.

90
00:05:28.080 --> 00:05:31.500
And I think we need to start thinking about designing clinical trials around the

91
00:05:31.520 --> 00:05:35.460
biological age and not necessarily chronological age to

92
00:05:35.520 --> 00:05:37.380
improve treatment of older patients.

93
00:05:38.140 --> 00:05:41.720
And so with this, we're going to have four talk, and the first one is going to be

94
00:05:41.780 --> 00:05:42.720
from Ari Melnick

95
00:05:43.620 --> 00:05:46.010
from the Jose Carreras Leukemia Research Center.

96
00:05:47.940 --> 00:05:48.480
And I'll try

97
00:05:49.340 --> 00:05:49.780
to get

98
00:05:52.680 --> 00:05:54.300
the slides. Ari?

99
00:05:54.920 --> 00:05:55.220
Yes.

100
00:06:00.856 --> 00:06:01.116
Great.

101
00:06:02.196 --> 00:06:06.116
I want to thank ACR for the chance to talk to you about some of our work, and Olga

102
00:06:06.156 --> 00:06:08.936
for organizing this session and the outstanding introduction.

103
00:06:10.196 --> 00:06:13.696
So the title of my talk is "Role of Sex and Ancestry in Inflammaging,

104
00:06:13.836 --> 00:06:17.815
Lymphomagenesis and Its Precision Therapy." I recently moved to

105
00:06:17.876 --> 00:06:19.436
Barcelona from the US

106
00:06:20.456 --> 00:06:24.206
to lead the Josep Carreras Leukemia Research Center, which is a freestanding

107
00:06:24.296 --> 00:06:27.896
blood cancer research institute that is embedded in multiple different hospitals

108
00:06:27.916 --> 00:06:29.836
and sites, and now also has a site in China.

109
00:06:30.776 --> 00:06:32.796
And it's a wonderful place. These are my disclosures.

110
00:06:33.656 --> 00:06:37.596
So already these discussions about inflammaging were

111
00:06:37.796 --> 00:06:41.456
extremely well covered by Olga. But I wanted to mention a couple of points

112
00:06:41.516 --> 00:06:45.156
related to immune system neoplasms, which is that

113
00:06:45.856 --> 00:06:46.436
there is a

114
00:06:47.676 --> 00:06:50.516
expansion of so-called aged B cells that occurs over time

115
00:06:51.376 --> 00:06:52.156
as people age.

116
00:06:53.296 --> 00:06:56.336
I'll get back to these, but these are these strange Tbet positive,

117
00:06:56.376 --> 00:07:00.136
TLR7 innate sensing B cells that are

118
00:07:00.146 --> 00:07:01.816
associated with aging and autoimmunity.

119
00:07:02.656 --> 00:07:05.846
It's also known that autoimmunity and chronic inflammatory conditions, which of

120
00:07:05.876 --> 00:07:09.776
course increase with age, are linked to increased risk of lymphomas such as

121
00:07:09.816 --> 00:07:13.476
the DLBCL, which are the most common blood cancer, and marginal zone

122
00:07:13.496 --> 00:07:16.796
lymphomas. And it's well established that many lymphomas have a tumor

123
00:07:16.856 --> 00:07:20.736
microenvironment reflecting a variety of distinct inflammatory

124
00:07:20.746 --> 00:07:22.656
scenarios that we don't really understand very well.

125
00:07:23.836 --> 00:07:26.856
So I'm going to focus the talk on, again, the most common blood cancers, which are

126
00:07:26.896 --> 00:07:30.716
diffuse large B-cell lymphomas. It's not a disease.

127
00:07:30.796 --> 00:07:34.736
This is a spectrum of tumors that we don't yet really have a good

128
00:07:34.776 --> 00:07:36.236
way to distinguish from each other.

129
00:07:36.316 --> 00:07:37.256
But there have been

130
00:07:38.136 --> 00:07:41.516
one useful classification is based on somatic mutation profiling, which captures at

131
00:07:41.556 --> 00:07:45.126
least a number of these cases. And I'm going to talk about

132
00:07:45.216 --> 00:07:46.586
the two types that

133
00:07:47.556 --> 00:07:51.296
we have the most solid data for inflammatory mechanisms, which are the MCDs, which

134
00:07:51.316 --> 00:07:55.216
do quite poorly, and then the BN2s, which occur especially in much

135
00:07:55.256 --> 00:07:58.796
older individuals. And then I'll talk about a new kind that's not even contemplated

136
00:07:58.836 --> 00:08:00.136
in this classification system.

137
00:08:00.996 --> 00:08:03.436
So let's get back to those AIBCs or ABCs.

138
00:08:03.576 --> 00:08:06.536
These are B cells that accumulate with aging.

139
00:08:07.116 --> 00:08:10.996
They are strange. They express myeloid surface markers like

140
00:08:11.016 --> 00:08:14.856
CD11c and CD11b. They express Tbet, which is

141
00:08:15.156 --> 00:08:17.436
a T cell transcription factor usually.

142
00:08:17.816 --> 00:08:21.765
They can undergo mutagenesis by expressing activation-induced cytidine

143
00:08:21.796 --> 00:08:24.416
deaminase when they're activated.

144
00:08:25.036 --> 00:08:28.276
And they can interface with various other cells in the microenvironment.

145
00:08:28.346 --> 00:08:31.096
They respond to various kinds of infections, and they're very labile.

146
00:08:31.436 --> 00:08:34.096
So these are B cells that kind of become activated

147
00:08:35.016 --> 00:08:38.576
at relatively low thresholds of stimulation which can be problematic.

148
00:08:39.336 --> 00:08:39.576
And

149
00:08:40.576 --> 00:08:44.296
as the names indicates, these cells are largely autoreactive, so

150
00:08:44.336 --> 00:08:48.116
they're IgM-positive cells that react to self-antigens.

151
00:08:48.136 --> 00:08:51.936
And normally these populations are supposed to be kept in check, and they are the

152
00:08:51.976 --> 00:08:53.756
basis for many autoimmune disorders.

153
00:08:53.796 --> 00:08:57.716
And it's been shown first by Chris Goodnow that in certain B cell-based

154
00:08:57.736 --> 00:09:01.616
autoimmune disorders, the B cells actually contain lymphoma somatic mutations,

155
00:09:01.756 --> 00:09:05.736
indicating that at least a subset of autoimmune disorders are in fact

156
00:09:05.776 --> 00:09:09.376
incipient lymphomas. And this is consistent with the fact of the risk these

157
00:09:09.436 --> 00:09:11.436
patients have for developing lymphomas later on.

158
00:09:12.936 --> 00:09:13.116
So,

159
00:09:14.716 --> 00:09:17.976
this first part I'll make very brief talking about those MCD

160
00:09:18.036 --> 00:09:21.816
DLBCLs, which are one of the most aggressive of all lymphomas and difficult to

161
00:09:21.876 --> 00:09:22.136
treat.

162
00:09:22.976 --> 00:09:26.876
Work conducted by Leandro Venturuti, who now has a laboratory at the British

163
00:09:26.916 --> 00:09:28.196
Columbia Cancer Agency.

164
00:09:29.116 --> 00:09:32.636
Summarized here, he explored the impact of two

165
00:09:32.676 --> 00:09:36.276
canonical MCD mutations. One is a hotspot mutation

166
00:09:36.336 --> 00:09:37.336
affecting the TLR

167
00:09:38.156 --> 00:09:41.976
adapter protein MyD88. Another one is affecting a corepressor protein

168
00:09:42.036 --> 00:09:42.996
called TIE2-1XR1.

169
00:09:44.636 --> 00:09:47.936
Very surprising findings for us were that either of these mutations

170
00:09:48.476 --> 00:09:52.036
reprogram the B cells that undergo the adaptive immune response

171
00:09:52.796 --> 00:09:54.136
are called germinal center B cells.

172
00:09:54.576 --> 00:09:56.936
So they form only transiently when we have an infection.

173
00:09:57.616 --> 00:10:01.356
And most lymphomas actually arise from those cells.

174
00:10:01.466 --> 00:10:03.336
And what Leandro found is that

175
00:10:04.196 --> 00:10:06.906
either of these mutations, which are quite different, the signaling protein

176
00:10:07.156 --> 00:10:11.126
co-repressor, they both result in the same perturbation, which is that

177
00:10:11.156 --> 00:10:15.045
they now deviate the normal path of development of germinal

178
00:10:15.116 --> 00:10:18.906
center B cells into forming aberrant autoimmune or aged B

179
00:10:18.916 --> 00:10:22.846
cells. These B cells accumulate, they become clonal, they

180
00:10:22.876 --> 00:10:26.296
accumulate over time, and they clearly can either lead

181
00:10:26.376 --> 00:10:29.756
to autoimmune disorders or they can lead to lymphoma or both.

182
00:10:29.896 --> 00:10:31.436
We don't really know these trajectories.

183
00:10:32.376 --> 00:10:35.656
They're different, how they overlap, how they talk to each other.

184
00:10:36.036 --> 00:10:37.156
But it does suggest that

185
00:10:38.236 --> 00:10:42.056
these AIBCs may be the clonal precursor

186
00:10:42.136 --> 00:10:45.156
cell for this whole set of lymphomas, which are quite aggressive.

187
00:10:45.216 --> 00:10:49.036
And we hypothesized that the pathway to transformation of these cells involves

188
00:10:49.276 --> 00:10:53.156
the emergence of a mutant AIBC from a germinal center reaction

189
00:10:53.716 --> 00:10:57.376
after affinity maturation. And these cells, we know they disseminate throughout the

190
00:10:57.416 --> 00:11:00.616
body. These types of lymphomas are, in fact

191
00:11:01.616 --> 00:11:03.076
very disseminated when they present.

192
00:11:03.236 --> 00:11:06.156
They tend to be extranodal, so the cells are all over the place.

193
00:11:06.836 --> 00:11:07.076
And

194
00:11:08.216 --> 00:11:12.116
because there's abundant self-antigen, they're continuously primed to be able to

195
00:11:12.126 --> 00:11:16.026
activate. And you can imagine that with even low levels of inflammation, over time,

196
00:11:16.056 --> 00:11:19.776
they're going to accumulate mutations since they express AID, and you'll eventually

197
00:11:19.786 --> 00:11:23.636
get some kind of inflammatory niche that's malignant, that will lead to these kind

198
00:11:23.676 --> 00:11:27.456
of hot lymphomas, many of which have a very cytotoxic T

199
00:11:27.576 --> 00:11:31.346
cell-rich microenvironment unless they acquire secondarily and

200
00:11:31.376 --> 00:11:34.946
later mutations that knock out MHC class 1, which happens fairly

201
00:11:34.976 --> 00:11:38.666
frequently. I don't have time to get into that, but it's another

202
00:11:38.676 --> 00:11:39.336
interesting angle.

203
00:11:40.436 --> 00:11:42.286
But that's old. So let me go to new things.

204
00:11:43.216 --> 00:11:46.946
I want to talk to you about BN2 DLBCLs, which is a newly defined entity from

205
00:11:47.596 --> 00:11:50.396
Luz Staudt and others from somatic mutation classifying.

206
00:11:51.276 --> 00:11:54.786
I do have a QR code I'll show a couple of times because the work I'm going to tell

207
00:11:54.796 --> 00:11:57.876
you about now is coming out during this session in "Cancer Discovery,"

208
00:11:59.056 --> 00:12:02.976
my favorite journal. And I'll tell you the reason why we really got into the

209
00:12:03.016 --> 00:12:06.116
BN2 DLBCLs originally is because it had been noted that they have frequent

210
00:12:06.136 --> 00:12:10.076
mutations of this gene called SPEN.And in my lab, we do

211
00:12:10.096 --> 00:12:13.156
things when I get curious about something, that's how we choose to do a project.

212
00:12:13.186 --> 00:12:16.556
And I was curious about SPEN because I like epigenetic mechanisms.

213
00:12:16.636 --> 00:12:20.416
And SPEN is known to be a repressor of Notch signaling, and also

214
00:12:20.676 --> 00:12:23.746
during development is important for inactivating X chromosome.

215
00:12:24.716 --> 00:12:25.036
So

216
00:12:26.036 --> 00:12:28.376
we explored a bit more the pattern of mutations of SPEN.

217
00:12:28.436 --> 00:12:29.236
It turns out that

218
00:12:30.456 --> 00:12:33.436
it's one of the founding mutations of the BN2 DLBCLs.

219
00:12:34.036 --> 00:12:37.536
SPEN is mutated across many cancers, but the truncation mutants are really only

220
00:12:37.616 --> 00:12:41.486
common in DLBCL. In solid tumors, they're much less fraction of

221
00:12:41.536 --> 00:12:45.096
the mutations. We wanted to understand more about the mutational

222
00:12:45.136 --> 00:12:48.536
context and found that by far the most significantly co-occurring

223
00:12:48.916 --> 00:12:52.756
mutation with SPEN were these truncating mutations in Notch2.

224
00:12:53.776 --> 00:12:57.556
Truncating mutations in Notch2 are also mainly a characteristic of DLBCL,

225
00:12:57.716 --> 00:12:59.876
not found really very much in solid cancers.

226
00:13:00.436 --> 00:13:04.256
And when these mutations are co-occurrent, patients seem to do quite

227
00:13:04.276 --> 00:13:07.956
poorly. We put together a cohort of about 4,500 DLBCL patients that have been

228
00:13:07.996 --> 00:13:11.756
sequenced, and the double mutation in this large

229
00:13:11.796 --> 00:13:13.536
cohort seems to be linked to inferior outcome.

230
00:13:13.556 --> 00:13:16.816
And so we thought we were onto something interesting to explore.

231
00:13:17.396 --> 00:13:20.996
Knowing mutational context helps one to model the disease, and so we obviously

232
00:13:21.036 --> 00:13:24.156
developed the animal models for SPEN truncation,

233
00:13:24.216 --> 00:13:27.856
Notch2 gain-of-function to assess whether they're

234
00:13:27.876 --> 00:13:31.756
cooperating. It was odd to me because since SPEN is assumed to be the same

235
00:13:31.816 --> 00:13:35.236
thing as Notch mutations, that kind of didn't fit this co-occurrence pattern.

236
00:13:36.816 --> 00:13:40.416
To make a long story short, the main phenotype that we

237
00:13:40.436 --> 00:13:43.796
observed in early time points in these double mutant animals was

238
00:13:43.836 --> 00:13:47.576
accumulation of AIBCs again. But these AIBCs are

239
00:13:47.586 --> 00:13:50.636
not the same ones I mentioned to you before. They're actually quite different.

240
00:13:50.676 --> 00:13:52.926
They're not coming out of adaptive immune response.

241
00:13:52.936 --> 00:13:56.716
They come from a totally different branch of the immune system, which is the innate

242
00:13:57.256 --> 00:13:58.186
part of the immune system,

243
00:13:59.256 --> 00:14:03.206
which is mediated by so-called marginal zone B cells that

244
00:14:03.216 --> 00:14:06.476
kind of monitor blood for pathogens.

245
00:14:07.036 --> 00:14:10.976
These AIBCs were the cell type that became clonal and expanded over

246
00:14:11.016 --> 00:14:14.476
time, which kind of was a mirror to some extent the

247
00:14:14.496 --> 00:14:17.395
previous scenario that I mentioned to you, but through a totally different pathway.

248
00:14:18.395 --> 00:14:22.376
And when the mice got lymphomas, and these lymphomas were

249
00:14:22.556 --> 00:14:26.536
rich in AIBCs. And then we looked in primary human patients and

250
00:14:26.576 --> 00:14:30.096
found that human patients also have the presence of the mouse lymphoma

251
00:14:30.116 --> 00:14:33.416
signature and also were enriched for this AIBC-type signature.

252
00:14:33.436 --> 00:14:37.416
And you can even see in Hyperion staining, the CD11c positive lymphoma

253
00:14:37.456 --> 00:14:40.536
cells present in the primary human lymphomas.

254
00:14:41.776 --> 00:14:41.976
So

255
00:14:43.896 --> 00:14:44.316
Benedict

256
00:14:46.556 --> 00:14:50.316
mentioned to me, "I noticed that in our mouse cohort that it's really the female

257
00:14:50.376 --> 00:14:53.276
mice that are dying, but not the males." And we were like, "Hmm,

258
00:14:54.216 --> 00:14:57.756
we usually ignore that. We don't really pay a lot of attention to that, to our

259
00:14:57.796 --> 00:15:01.416
detriment." NIH tells you you have to have gender-balanced mice.

260
00:15:01.896 --> 00:15:03.486
Now I know why that is because this really

261
00:15:04.356 --> 00:15:04.696
matters.

262
00:15:05.836 --> 00:15:08.316
And we looked in the human patients, and it turns out that the patients who are

263
00:15:08.376 --> 00:15:11.756
actually dying with these two mutations are actually the women, but not the men.

264
00:15:12.696 --> 00:15:15.516
So the phenotype seems to be much more severe in females.

265
00:15:16.296 --> 00:15:18.416
We did many experiments, which I won't go into,

266
00:15:19.236 --> 00:15:21.656
but concluded that this must be an X chromosome effect.

267
00:15:21.676 --> 00:15:25.456
We ruled out hormones, et cetera. In fact, many of the patients are

268
00:15:25.496 --> 00:15:27.426
quite elderly, so may have

269
00:15:28.596 --> 00:15:32.406
lower hormone levels. And so we wondered, so this made us kind of

270
00:15:32.436 --> 00:15:36.086
switch our thinking a bit to thinking about maybe this is something about SPEN and

271
00:15:36.236 --> 00:15:39.936
failure to properly maintain X chromosome

272
00:15:40.036 --> 00:15:40.816
silencing

273
00:15:41.876 --> 00:15:42.696
in B cells.

274
00:15:45.456 --> 00:15:49.036
One of the ways to measure that is to look at X chromosome status and methylation

275
00:15:49.116 --> 00:15:52.836
patterning. And we observed indeed that in the SN2 lymphomas, there is a

276
00:15:52.876 --> 00:15:55.856
reduction. It's not spectacularly dramatic, but it's there,

277
00:15:57.176 --> 00:15:59.996
and significant in X chromosome status and methylation.

278
00:16:01.136 --> 00:16:03.016
But we don't see that in the autosomes.

279
00:16:03.256 --> 00:16:05.396
So it's an X chromosome-specific effect.

280
00:16:06.096 --> 00:16:06.316
Now

281
00:16:07.616 --> 00:16:10.836
this to us, I've worked in the epigenetic field many years.

282
00:16:11.216 --> 00:16:15.176
This kind of mild signal that's not

283
00:16:15.216 --> 00:16:18.976
very robustly confined to particular CpGs is suggestive of a kind of

284
00:16:18.996 --> 00:16:22.276
stochastic effect where there's instability of epigenetic regulation.

285
00:16:22.336 --> 00:16:23.016
And perhaps

286
00:16:24.856 --> 00:16:28.595
there are a number of important immune genes on the X chromosome,

287
00:16:28.636 --> 00:16:32.456
including TLR7. TLR7 is a critical driver of autoimmune

288
00:16:32.476 --> 00:16:36.316
disorders and AIBCs. And in fact, if you look at TLR7

289
00:16:36.356 --> 00:16:39.116
locus, the TLR7 locus is hypomethylated.

290
00:16:40.336 --> 00:16:44.276
And so there seems to be selection for hypomethylation at genes that are likely to

291
00:16:44.316 --> 00:16:48.136
confer fitness on these B cells. We

292
00:16:48.276 --> 00:16:51.456
compared and contrasted the male and female lymphomas and found that AIBCs are

293
00:16:51.516 --> 00:16:53.636
actually more abundant in the females.

294
00:16:53.976 --> 00:16:57.586
This mirrors what happens in aging, where AIBCs are also more common in females.

295
00:16:58.136 --> 00:17:01.896
We also noted that the female lymphomas had higher levels of TLR7.

296
00:17:02.576 --> 00:17:06.156
And in a functional experiment, TLR7 agonists more potently

297
00:17:06.196 --> 00:17:09.856
stimulated the activity of the female cells versus the male cells.

298
00:17:09.936 --> 00:17:10.146
And

299
00:17:11.096 --> 00:17:15.017
there was a threshold effect whereby female cells activate at low

300
00:17:15.076 --> 00:17:18.636
levels of TLR signaling. Finally, we wondered if there is an opportunity for

301
00:17:18.656 --> 00:17:22.576
precision therapy. There are drugs that block the TLR7 pathway.

302
00:17:23.096 --> 00:17:26.716
It signals through IRAK kinases. There are IRAK kinase inhibitors in clinical

303
00:17:26.757 --> 00:17:30.676
trials. Comparing female and male mice, we observed that the

304
00:17:31.516 --> 00:17:35.256
IC50 for IRAK inhibitors was quite a bit lower in the females versus

305
00:17:35.316 --> 00:17:38.376
males. So there's a sex-specific response to the drugs.

306
00:17:38.946 --> 00:17:41.976
And we were lucky to obtain a primary human

307
00:17:43.056 --> 00:17:46.946
female SN2 lymphoma that we could engraft in mice,

308
00:17:46.996 --> 00:17:50.676
and we gave an IRAK inhibitor there and also observed that there was a

309
00:17:50.696 --> 00:17:54.396
response to this as well, suggesting that the potential

310
00:17:54.436 --> 00:17:57.856
concept of a sex-specific precision therapy for this

311
00:17:57.916 --> 00:18:01.456
inflammaging type phenotype is something that may be possible,

312
00:18:02.276 --> 00:18:05.056
and worth exploring further. I think there's a lot more work to do to expand on

313
00:18:05.076 --> 00:18:05.856
this point. But

314
00:18:06.716 --> 00:18:10.555
yeah, it's something that we never imagined.And we think we've

315
00:18:10.586 --> 00:18:14.126
uncovered an X instability

316
00:18:14.166 --> 00:18:17.406
phenotype that may be relevant even beyond these tumors.

317
00:18:17.426 --> 00:18:21.196
As I mentioned to you before, ESTAR mutations occur beyond DLBCLs.

318
00:18:21.266 --> 00:18:23.846
I think it would be a good idea to start to look for these associations.

319
00:18:23.906 --> 00:18:26.906
We know that cancer outcomes are different in women in other tumor types as well.

320
00:18:27.846 --> 00:18:29.826
We don't know if this is at play, but it needs to be looked at.

321
00:18:29.986 --> 00:18:33.766
And again, here's the QR code if you would like to take a look and see in more

322
00:18:33.786 --> 00:18:34.926
detail what's there.

323
00:18:35.726 --> 00:18:39.206
I'll close with this question about ancestry, which

324
00:18:39.226 --> 00:18:42.546
another sort of inflammaging surprise to us.

325
00:18:44.346 --> 00:18:47.826
It's important to know that in the United States, African American patients with

326
00:18:47.846 --> 00:18:51.246
diffuse large B-cell lymphomas are diagnosed at an earlier age, so they get it

327
00:18:51.326 --> 00:18:51.556
younger,

328
00:18:52.586 --> 00:18:55.026
and have worse survival compared to non-Hispanic whites.

329
00:18:55.426 --> 00:18:58.956
Patients with African ancestry have been historically underrepresented in clinical

330
00:18:58.966 --> 00:19:02.946
trials, and the studies that led to the existing molecular classifications of

331
00:19:02.966 --> 00:19:03.446
the disease.

332
00:19:04.246 --> 00:19:07.706
And whereas socioeconomic factors impact clinical outcome, they do not seem to

333
00:19:07.726 --> 00:19:11.586
explain the diagnosis at younger age, and depending on which expert you listen

334
00:19:11.626 --> 00:19:15.336
to, they may also reflect biological differences in these

335
00:19:15.346 --> 00:19:19.196
patients. So, this is work that was done with Chris Flower, Gene

336
00:19:19.286 --> 00:19:23.066
Koff, Yuri Fedory. It was conducted by Sanket Shah, who was a

337
00:19:23.106 --> 00:19:27.006
postdoc in the lab. And Chris had published

338
00:19:27.026 --> 00:19:30.346
this paper a few years ago showing that the spectrum of somatic mutations in

339
00:19:30.486 --> 00:19:33.926
African Americans with DLBCL was not exactly the same as

340
00:19:34.006 --> 00:19:37.666
Europeans. And the most striking finding were frequent mutations

341
00:19:37.786 --> 00:19:41.386
of ATM, MGA, and SETD2, all three of which are DNA damage

342
00:19:41.526 --> 00:19:42.326
sensing genes,

343
00:19:43.286 --> 00:19:45.046
and which occur in more than 50% of patients.

344
00:19:45.706 --> 00:19:49.266
We wanted to validate this, so we did a sequencing

345
00:19:49.326 --> 00:19:52.366
profiling in an independent cohort of patients that we obtained from Paul

346
00:19:52.386 --> 00:19:55.826
Rubinstein. And then Yuri has a program exploring

347
00:19:56.046 --> 00:19:59.456
lymphomagenesis in Malawi in Africa, and his African patients also had the

348
00:19:59.506 --> 00:20:03.466
same frequency of mutations. And so this reflects this is not something

349
00:20:03.486 --> 00:20:05.986
that happens to Africans when they move to the West.

350
00:20:06.066 --> 00:20:09.486
It's actually something that is part of their genetic ancestry.

351
00:20:10.886 --> 00:20:14.366
We also explored the microenvironment in these

352
00:20:14.446 --> 00:20:18.146
lymphomas. This is using CODEX and Luna4 staining, and the most striking

353
00:20:18.245 --> 00:20:21.766
finding that we found really is increased frequency of

354
00:20:21.806 --> 00:20:25.796
exhausted CD4 and CD8 cells, but especially CD4 cells in

355
00:20:25.866 --> 00:20:28.426
African ancestry lymphomas. Curious.

356
00:20:29.106 --> 00:20:29.426
So,

357
00:20:30.686 --> 00:20:33.546
we had published a couple of years ago in "Cancer Discovery" that SETD2 help

358
00:20:33.556 --> 00:20:36.686
insufficiency drives lymphomagenesis through genomic instability.

359
00:20:37.246 --> 00:20:40.486
So we wondered if perhaps this inflammatory microenvironment was linked to these

360
00:20:40.506 --> 00:20:42.146
tumors having genomic instability.

361
00:20:42.566 --> 00:20:46.126
Staining for H2AX phosphorylation show that apparently there is a higher

362
00:20:46.186 --> 00:20:50.126
abundance of DNA damage in these lymphomas, comparing the African

363
00:20:50.166 --> 00:20:54.056
Americans. And then just doing single cell electrophoresis to see if

364
00:20:54.086 --> 00:20:57.986
you can really see the breaks. We do see both in the murine, our

365
00:20:58.026 --> 00:21:01.746
mouse models, such as lymphomas, as well as in the human cells, that there is

366
00:21:01.806 --> 00:21:04.166
increased evidence of ongoing genomic instability.

367
00:21:05.226 --> 00:21:08.606
So, how do you put this all together? No surprise to this audience.

368
00:21:08.686 --> 00:21:09.046
We

369
00:21:09.906 --> 00:21:13.766
wondered whether or not this may be linked to perhaps senescence-associated

370
00:21:13.806 --> 00:21:14.686
secretary phenotype

371
00:21:15.666 --> 00:21:16.166
occurring

372
00:21:17.266 --> 00:21:19.366
particularly in these African American DLBCLs.

373
00:21:20.046 --> 00:21:23.806
So we stained for senescence markers using various methods.

374
00:21:23.866 --> 00:21:25.786
Here I'm showing you GLB1 staining.

375
00:21:25.946 --> 00:21:29.686
These are four independent TMAs of African or African American

376
00:21:29.746 --> 00:21:33.546
versus four European cohorts. And we observed that the

377
00:21:33.646 --> 00:21:36.666
abundance of senescent cells is very obviously

378
00:21:37.926 --> 00:21:41.206
strongly increased in the African Americans, and they coincide

379
00:21:41.786 --> 00:21:45.206
with those mutations I mentioned to you earlier. So the mutations are present.

380
00:21:45.246 --> 00:21:46.666
You see the senescent phenotype.

381
00:21:48.646 --> 00:21:52.306
Looking closer at the cell communities within these lymphomas, we observed that

382
00:21:52.506 --> 00:21:56.406
the exhausted CD4 and CD8 cells are actually clustered around the senescent

383
00:21:56.426 --> 00:22:00.146
cells. So there's something about the senescent cells that's inducing exhaustion

384
00:22:00.266 --> 00:22:02.126
in the CD4 and CD8 cells.

385
00:22:03.786 --> 00:22:04.066
We

386
00:22:05.126 --> 00:22:08.916
were able to sort senescent positive and negative cells from the same lymphomas and

387
00:22:08.946 --> 00:22:12.686
test their functionality. I will tell you right now that these cells, the

388
00:22:12.706 --> 00:22:16.346
senescence positive cells proliferate the same as non-senescent cells.

389
00:22:16.466 --> 00:22:20.066
There is no growth arrest in this version of senescence, which

390
00:22:20.526 --> 00:22:23.966
is not surprising in B cells because B cells specialize in

391
00:22:24.006 --> 00:22:27.625
down-regulating the checkpoints that normally trigger senescence growth arrest.

392
00:22:28.226 --> 00:22:32.056
If you put these positive, negative cells into mice that are immunocompromised,

393
00:22:32.086 --> 00:22:35.986
they grow equally well. But you put them into mice that are immunocompetent, now

394
00:22:36.086 --> 00:22:39.366
only the senescent cells are able to form lymphomas, whereas the non-senescent

395
00:22:39.426 --> 00:22:43.306
cells are rejected, which together with the data I showed you in the

396
00:22:43.346 --> 00:22:46.746
previous slide, suggests that immunovasion in this context is explained

397
00:22:46.786 --> 00:22:49.586
by the subfraction of cells that are senescent.

398
00:22:51.006 --> 00:22:52.756
We did some T-cell depletion studies.

399
00:22:53.086 --> 00:22:55.886
This is either knocking out CD4 cells or CD8 cells.

400
00:22:55.926 --> 00:22:59.106
If you knock out CD8 cells, it doesn't impair tumorigenesis.

401
00:22:59.146 --> 00:23:02.786
If you knock out the CD4 cells, tumorigenesis is impaired, and you lose

402
00:23:02.826 --> 00:23:06.606
exhausted CD8 cells as well, suggesting that the mechanism here

403
00:23:06.686 --> 00:23:07.326
involves

404
00:23:08.946 --> 00:23:12.806
induction of some kind of functional state in CD4 cells that protects tumors from

405
00:23:12.826 --> 00:23:14.106
being attacked immunologically.

406
00:23:14.926 --> 00:23:18.786
We explored the signaling pathways and

407
00:23:18.886 --> 00:23:22.116
secretome of these cells. I don't have time to tell you about it, but it's the

408
00:23:22.116 --> 00:23:25.946
cytokine profiles that the senescent cells secrete are not exactly the

409
00:23:25.986 --> 00:23:28.726
same as have been observed and reported in cellular tumors.

410
00:23:28.866 --> 00:23:32.366
So there's certainly cell context specificity in the cytokine profiles, and it's

411
00:23:32.426 --> 00:23:35.986
not exactly the same. And so there may be immunological

412
00:23:36.066 --> 00:23:39.926
senescence-specific functions at play, which we are exploring.

413
00:23:40.046 --> 00:23:41.386
I don't have any punchlines on that.

414
00:23:42.706 --> 00:23:43.706
We wondered if

415
00:23:44.946 --> 00:23:48.366
targeting SETD2 itself might have a senolytic effect.

416
00:23:48.666 --> 00:23:52.596
SETD2, these tumors are always heterozygous, so the lymphomas with these

417
00:23:52.596 --> 00:23:54.326
mutations always are heterozygous.

418
00:23:54.846 --> 00:23:58.466
They don't tolerate knocking out the other allele, which led us to wonder if we

419
00:23:58.506 --> 00:24:02.066
could put these tumor cells over the threshold of linear damage that would be

420
00:24:02.086 --> 00:24:05.986
impossible for them to tolerate. And in fact, we observed that they are

421
00:24:06.026 --> 00:24:08.126
quite sensitive to inhibitional SETD2 inhibitors.

422
00:24:09.126 --> 00:24:09.356
And

423
00:24:10.166 --> 00:24:13.386
this is a clinical SETD2 inhibitor that was in clinical trials until the

424
00:24:13.426 --> 00:24:17.026
company decided to change focus. We are trying to buy the drug

425
00:24:17.046 --> 00:24:21.026
back so we can do clinical trials in African Americans who might perhaps

426
00:24:21.106 --> 00:24:24.882
benefit from this therapy.So the summary of this last

427
00:24:24.982 --> 00:24:28.482
part is that what we discovered is a novel African variant

428
00:24:28.782 --> 00:24:32.322
type of lymphoma that doesn't seem to occur very often in European ancestry

429
00:24:32.342 --> 00:24:35.822
individuals. It is driven by a SAS-like program that creates an

430
00:24:35.862 --> 00:24:39.302
inflammatory immune-suppressive microenvironment through CD4 cells.

431
00:24:40.062 --> 00:24:42.842
It's actually very important for Africa. It's very easy to diagnose.

432
00:24:42.942 --> 00:24:46.502
A single histochemistry stain that costs $20 is enough to know

433
00:24:46.922 --> 00:24:49.472
if the patients have it or not. If they're SAS-positive, if they're

434
00:24:49.562 --> 00:24:51.002
senescence-positive, then they have it.

435
00:24:51.502 --> 00:24:54.062
And this is important because those patients could be then enrolled in

436
00:24:55.862 --> 00:24:58.602
SAS-specific therapy. I want to also mention that

437
00:25:00.222 --> 00:25:00.702
the

438
00:25:01.522 --> 00:25:05.302
studies from multiple groups suggest that there is accelerating biological

439
00:25:05.382 --> 00:25:09.222
aging in Africans in general, and so the earlier

440
00:25:09.262 --> 00:25:13.142
occurrence of these and many other tumor types probably reflect early-onset

441
00:25:13.202 --> 00:25:17.132
inflammaaging in this population, which leads to all kinds of tumors and not just

442
00:25:17.142 --> 00:25:21.022
lymphomas. And then there's a potential ancestry-specific precision therapy

443
00:25:21.042 --> 00:25:23.122
approach, where using CD2 inhibitors or

444
00:25:23.942 --> 00:25:27.281
immune checkpoint inhibitors, which have not been successful against other DLBCLs,

445
00:25:27.861 --> 00:25:31.162
but in these model systems seem to be quite dramatically active.

446
00:25:32.062 --> 00:25:35.662
So last slide. We've covered three different mechanisms linked to

447
00:25:35.722 --> 00:25:39.562
inflammaaging. The first two were in the MCD DLBCLs with the

448
00:25:39.602 --> 00:25:41.982
terminal center-derived IBCs, the

449
00:25:43.782 --> 00:25:46.862
BN2 DLBCLs, which have female-specific

450
00:25:47.582 --> 00:25:48.762
biological characteristics.

451
00:25:49.902 --> 00:25:52.762
Both of these top two are linked to aging.

452
00:25:52.922 --> 00:25:55.772
They both occur much more frequently in aging and especially the BN2s.

453
00:25:56.232 --> 00:26:00.132
Whereas the African variant occurs apparently at a younger age, but because these

454
00:26:00.162 --> 00:26:03.572
patients actually manifest perhaps an accelerated aging or senescence phenotype.

455
00:26:04.522 --> 00:26:08.402
So many roads to inflammaaging in immune system

456
00:26:08.522 --> 00:26:12.322
cancers and potential multiple therapeutic opportunities for intervening

457
00:26:12.942 --> 00:26:15.402
and potential diagnostic approaches for detecting them.

458
00:26:15.842 --> 00:26:19.502
And that's all I have to say. So thank you very much. These are our collaborators.

459
00:26:20.702 --> 00:26:21.722
I point you to this website.

460
00:26:28.382 --> 00:26:28.842
Hi, Ari.

461
00:26:29.062 --> 00:26:29.462
Hey, Ben.

462
00:26:30.042 --> 00:26:30.742
Nice to see you.

463
00:26:30.982 --> 00:26:31.632
Good to see you.

464
00:26:31.662 --> 00:26:33.482
I have two questions, one on each part.

465
00:26:33.961 --> 00:26:37.502
So if you just mutate the SPEN1, do you get a marginal zone lymphoma?

466
00:26:38.462 --> 00:26:41.502
If you just mutate SPEN1 haploinsufficient like you have in

467
00:26:42.782 --> 00:26:45.082
human beings, you really don't get lymphomas. It's not enough.

468
00:26:45.342 --> 00:26:47.842
No lymph, but you don't get any marginal zone proliferation or any-

469
00:26:47.922 --> 00:26:49.482
You get a little bit.

470
00:26:50.502 --> 00:26:53.762
NotCH2, marginal zones, you know. That's been well shown.

471
00:26:55.342 --> 00:26:58.182
SPEN homozygous knockout has a marginal zone phenotype.

472
00:26:58.222 --> 00:26:58.682
Okay.

473
00:26:58.702 --> 00:27:02.602
But the haploinsufficient one, you kind of see

474
00:27:03.482 --> 00:27:05.562
it because you know that it's supposed to be there, but it's not really very

475
00:27:05.602 --> 00:27:06.162
noticeable.

476
00:27:06.462 --> 00:27:10.172
Okay. And on the second part of the talk, maybe I missed this, but what's the

477
00:27:10.182 --> 00:27:13.762
connection between African ancestry and developing those mutations?

478
00:27:14.622 --> 00:27:17.702
This is the question that a new post-doc has asked me that question.

479
00:27:17.802 --> 00:27:18.302
I think that

480
00:27:19.562 --> 00:27:23.422
it's known that Africans have a number of DNA

481
00:27:23.482 --> 00:27:24.322
damage sensing

482
00:27:25.342 --> 00:27:27.622
hypomorphic alleles, especially P53.

483
00:27:28.702 --> 00:27:31.582
But also there are papers that show multiple other genes like that, and we're

484
00:27:31.642 --> 00:27:33.382
exploring if that's relevant or not.

