00:32:03.814 --> 00:32:07.414
have worse outcomes. They suffer more deaths.

571
00:32:09.094 --> 00:32:13.074
The problem here is that although older patients

572
00:32:13.194 --> 00:32:16.874
comprise, in the real world, over half of breast

573
00:32:16.954 --> 00:32:20.864
cancer diagnoses and over 40% of

574
00:32:20.914 --> 00:32:24.834
breast cancer-related deaths, they're only represented in clinical trials at

575
00:32:24.894 --> 00:32:26.694
about 25% right now.

576
00:32:28.294 --> 00:32:30.894
Middle-aged women, on the other hand, comprise

577
00:32:30.934 --> 00:32:33.574
anywhere from 75% to

578
00:32:33.794 --> 00:32:36.974
95% of participants in clinical trials.

579
00:32:37.034 --> 00:32:39.554
And likewise, because younger patients

580
00:32:40.574 --> 00:32:41.963
are facing

581
00:32:42.954 --> 00:32:46.934
lower incidents, although we're hearing more and more about young onset breast

582
00:32:47.034 --> 00:32:50.454
cancer, they too are underrepresented in trials.

583
00:32:50.514 --> 00:32:53.934
So it poses a few challenges to trying to

584
00:32:54.414 --> 00:32:56.554
understand why those outcomes are worse.

585
00:32:57.014 --> 00:33:00.974
Number one, it says to me that how likely are real-world outcomes

586
00:33:01.034 --> 00:33:03.314
to reflect what we're seeing in our clinical trials?

587
00:33:03.654 --> 00:33:07.124
And number two, we may be missing very important opportunities for care and

588
00:33:07.194 --> 00:33:11.023
treatment of younger and older patients by not focusing on

589
00:33:11.054 --> 00:33:14.523
those, and also conducting research in much younger animals,

590
00:33:14.594 --> 00:33:15.154
typically.

591
00:33:17.114 --> 00:33:21.034
So I would like to address first, the very first question

592
00:33:21.074 --> 00:33:25.034
we asked, given those differences in outcome, are breast

593
00:33:25.114 --> 00:33:26.594
cancers different with age?

594
00:33:27.934 --> 00:33:31.854
Somewhat simple question, very tough to answer, but I would

595
00:33:31.864 --> 00:33:35.634
like to mention Dr. Adrienne Parsons and Esther Soares Colon in my lab,

596
00:33:36.034 --> 00:33:40.014
along with our colleague and collaborator in my division, another PI,

