1204
01:08:52.391 --> 01:08:56.340
to healthy controls, and patients with pancreatic cancer compared to all

1205
01:08:56.391 --> 01:08:57.730
other types of cancer that were in here.

1206
01:08:57.870 --> 01:09:01.590
This is pan-solid tumors, so no heme malignancies, and it's

1207
01:09:01.630 --> 01:09:05.580
controlled for age. And if we look at this in patients with pancreas

1208
01:09:05.610 --> 01:09:09.391
cancer, we were interested in this molecule GDF15, which is

1209
01:09:09.450 --> 01:09:13.410
high versus healthy controls and high compared to patients with other

1210
01:09:13.450 --> 01:09:14.190
types of cancer.

1211
01:09:15.410 --> 01:09:19.190
And we were interested in it because it's a molecule that kind of fit a lot of the

1212
01:09:19.210 --> 01:09:22.650
things that we were looking at in terms of the phenotypes we saw in our models and

1213
01:09:22.690 --> 01:09:25.431
the behavior of tumors we see in patients.

1214
01:09:25.490 --> 01:09:29.150
So, very interestingly, this is one of the prototypic age-associated

1215
01:09:29.190 --> 01:09:32.250
molecules that increases steadily throughout the lifespan.

1216
01:09:32.870 --> 01:09:36.130
It's associated with decreased T cell priming and impaired trafficking in a number

1217
01:09:36.210 --> 01:09:37.909
of normal physiologic functions.

1218
01:09:38.830 --> 01:09:40.330
It's actually the driver of

1219
01:09:41.431 --> 01:09:44.790
morning sickness in pregnant women, which is interesting because it's hard to

1220
01:09:44.830 --> 01:09:48.431
understand where it's working. And the known receptor is predominantly on brain

1221
01:09:48.490 --> 01:09:52.400
stem neurons, but very clearly it affects immune cells through a couple different

1222
01:09:52.410 --> 01:09:54.430
diverse mechanisms that are still being worked out.

1223
01:09:55.090 --> 01:09:58.270
But nonetheless, even though we don't necessarily know the exact receptor on every

1224
01:09:58.290 --> 01:10:01.650
cell type in the immune system, there's been clinical activity to develop

1225
01:10:01.730 --> 01:10:04.790
neutralizing antibodies against this, so we can deal with the source of the

1226
01:10:04.810 --> 01:10:07.070
cytokine rather than necessarily the target of it.

1227
01:10:07.700 --> 01:10:11.270
And it's in trials looking at trying to improve cancer

1228
01:10:11.290 --> 01:10:14.840
cachexia, mostly through its actions on the brain stem neurons,

1229
01:10:14.970 --> 01:10:18.910
but also immunotherapy resistance in previously treated non-small cell lung

1230
01:10:18.990 --> 01:10:22.930
cancer. So we thought this could be an avenue towards, if it's relevant in our

1231
01:10:22.970 --> 01:10:25.130
models, improved outcomes for our patients.

1232
01:10:26.030 --> 01:10:28.330
Now, again, I told you this is an age-associated molecule.

1233
01:10:28.890 --> 01:10:32.450
I'm showing you here its expression in aged pancreatic fibroblasts from

1234
01:10:32.610 --> 01:10:35.390
older compared to younger donors. It's highly upregulated.

1235
01:10:36.050 --> 01:10:39.000
And I guess importantly here, that I'm also showing you that it's expressed in

1236
01:10:39.010 --> 01:10:42.970
patient tumors. Not only in the cancer cells, we can see here around the kind

1237
01:10:42.980 --> 01:10:46.930
of glandular structures, but also in the stroma, in the fibroblasts, in these cells

1238
01:10:46.970 --> 01:10:50.730
that are native to the host, not just malignant cells that have transformed.

1239
01:10:52.110 --> 01:10:55.890
I think if you look at TCGA data and stratify

1240
01:10:55.950 --> 01:10:59.670
patients with PDAC, high GDF15 expression versus lower GDF15

1241
01:10:59.710 --> 01:11:03.570
expression, you start to see things fall out that kind of give you a hint

1242
01:11:03.610 --> 01:11:06.550
that the immune system is really suppressed in these patients with high

1243
01:11:06.610 --> 01:11:09.650
GDF15. And just at a more broad level, if you

1244
01:11:11.350 --> 01:11:14.810
estimate the makeup of their immune infiltrate by these RNA sequencing metrics,

1245
01:11:15.610 --> 01:11:19.540
high GDF15 really shows that you're not going to get infiltration of

1246
01:11:19.590 --> 01:11:22.890
all these adaptive immune cell populations that we're hoping to see in pancreas

1247
01:11:22.950 --> 01:11:25.370
cancer that are not there in these immune excluded tumors.

1248
01:11:26.770 --> 01:11:30.450
So with that, we went back and looked at our mouse models, and I think one thing we

1249
01:11:30.490 --> 01:11:34.069
saw is in young mice, just like in younger humans, GDF15 levels are very low.

1250
01:11:34.810 --> 01:11:38.730
In aged mice, those rise, and interestingly to me here, if you put a tumor

1251
01:11:38.790 --> 01:11:42.590
into the pancreas of a young mouse, there's no change in circulating GDF15

1252
01:11:42.630 --> 01:11:46.570
levels. Whereas if you put it in an aged mouse, you get an increase in

1253
01:11:46.610 --> 01:11:50.390
GDF15 expression, kind of, again, copying what we saw where patients with pancreas

1254
01:11:50.410 --> 01:11:54.290
cancer get even higher GDF15 than those that don't have cancer.

1255
01:11:54.330 --> 01:11:56.910
And I think we only see that if you use an age-informed model.

1256
01:11:57.650 --> 01:11:59.550
GDF15 is also highly

1257
01:12:00.490 --> 01:12:04.390
expressed in the tumor itself in addition to

1258
01:12:04.430 --> 01:12:07.540
the circulation. So we thought this was, again, an interesting thing where it's

1259
01:12:07.570 --> 01:12:10.620
matching what we're seeing in our patients, and we're able to model it effectively

1260
01:12:10.630 --> 01:12:12.300
by using these aged mouse models.

1261
01:12:13.690 --> 01:12:16.270
Then we went through and wanted to say, what's its functional contribution to

1262
01:12:16.290 --> 01:12:18.610
anti-tumor immunity and immune infiltration?

1263
01:12:18.710 --> 01:12:22.470
So if you take a young GDF15 low mouse and you administer recombinant

1264
01:12:22.510 --> 01:12:26.380
GDF15, you get larger tumors, and you also drive down T cell

1265
01:12:26.430 --> 01:12:28.770
infiltration, CD8 T cell infiltration.

1266
01:12:29.710 --> 01:12:33.530
If you do the kind of opposite experiment, where you breed some GDF15 knockout

1267
01:12:33.590 --> 01:12:37.350
mice in their cohorts and their wild-type

1268
01:12:38.310 --> 01:12:42.030
controls, and you wait a year for them to have their birthday party, and then you

1269
01:12:42.070 --> 01:12:44.960
can finally do your experiment, you see that the tumors are smaller if you have

1270
01:12:44.990 --> 01:12:48.920
host knockout of GDF15, and you get an increase in CD8

1271
01:12:48.950 --> 01:12:52.200
T cell infiltration. So again, we thought this kind of linked the expression of

1272
01:12:52.210 --> 01:12:56.010
this molecule directly to T cell infiltration and immune exclusion in

1273
01:12:56.030 --> 01:12:56.830
pancreas cancer.

1274
01:12:58.130 --> 01:12:59.730
Now, again, what do we want to do with this, right?

1275
01:12:59.770 --> 01:13:03.110
We want to move this to somewhere where we can use this knowledge to improve

1276
01:13:03.150 --> 01:13:05.790
outcomes for patients. And again, to Dr.

1277
01:13:05.950 --> 01:13:09.530
McAllister's point, what agents are we leaving on the table if we're not thinking

1278
01:13:09.610 --> 01:13:12.590
about age-related changes in the tumor and host microenvironment?

1279
01:13:12.630 --> 01:13:16.250
And I'll show you here, if you do the experiment where you neutralize GDF15 in

1280
01:13:16.290 --> 01:13:18.510
young mice, you'd say, "This is a loser.

1281
01:13:19.050 --> 01:13:20.550
You're not going to pursue this anymore.

1282
01:13:20.590 --> 01:13:21.690
There's no difference in

1283
01:13:22.550 --> 01:13:26.390
tumor size here." But you get about a 50% reduction in

1284
01:13:26.430 --> 01:13:30.090
tumor size if you just do monotherapy neutralization of

1285
01:13:30.110 --> 01:13:32.010
GDF15 in those aged mouse

1286
01:13:32.150 --> 01:13:36.106
models.I think the other thing we wanted to

1287
01:13:36.126 --> 01:13:39.486
say, is this a T cell dependent phenomenon in terms of its efficacy?

1288
01:13:39.546 --> 01:13:43.526
And you can see if you neutralize GDF15, but you deplete

1289
01:13:43.586 --> 01:13:46.686
T cells, you lose that efficacy. Again, arguing that this is

1290
01:13:47.486 --> 01:13:51.125
probably an immune-related effect and something that we'd want to follow up on.

1291
01:13:52.266 --> 01:13:55.926
And if you take the T cells, the CD8 T cells, out of these mice after neutralizing

1292
01:13:55.966 --> 01:13:56.676
GDF15,

1293
01:13:57.646 --> 01:13:58.956
what you see in terms of their

1294
01:13:59.886 --> 01:14:03.456
gene set enrichment pathway analysis is that those T cells from the

1295
01:14:03.566 --> 01:14:07.466
mice without GDF15, the ones that got it neutralized, are primed to

1296
01:14:07.486 --> 01:14:10.286
respond in this more pro-inflammatory phenotype.

1297
01:14:11.726 --> 01:14:14.926
So with that, I think I told you it's great, we can get more T cells in there.

1298
01:14:14.986 --> 01:14:18.456
But one problem we're really up against in pancreas cancer is that there's not a

1299
01:14:18.486 --> 01:14:21.786
lot of them to begin with. And you need antigen-specific T

1300
01:14:21.846 --> 01:14:25.426
cells to then activate T cells to go and kill tumor cells.

1301
01:14:26.186 --> 01:14:30.066
So we're very interested in using cancer vaccine approaches to get those

1302
01:14:30.106 --> 01:14:33.786
neoantigen-specific T cells and then find ways to augment their activity,

1303
01:14:33.946 --> 01:14:37.446
potentially through modulating TME signals, to make them work better.

1304
01:14:38.606 --> 01:14:41.136
And with that, I've collaborated with great people at Johns Hopkins, like Dr.

1305
01:14:41.286 --> 01:14:45.226
Amanda Huff and Dr. Neha Zaidi, to look at the cancer

1306
01:14:45.246 --> 01:14:48.726
vaccine approaches, and they developed a wonderful mutant KRAS peptide vaccine,

1307
01:14:49.386 --> 01:14:52.726
which covers the six most common KRAS mutant

1308
01:14:53.266 --> 01:14:57.196
alleles in pancreas cancer, and this accounts for over 90% of the patients that

1309
01:14:57.226 --> 01:14:58.026
we see in the clinic.

1310
01:14:58.986 --> 01:15:02.226
But I think what we've seen in the clinic so far and the trials that they've used

1311
01:15:02.306 --> 01:15:05.386
here is that you can induce T cell responses in the periphery.

1312
01:15:05.526 --> 01:15:09.016
You can get neoantigen-specific T cells against mutant KRAS in the periphery, but

1313
01:15:09.026 --> 01:15:12.806
we're still struggling to get them into the tumors and to actually kill tumor cells

1314
01:15:12.846 --> 01:15:15.205
to result in decreased tumor size.

1315
01:15:16.106 --> 01:15:20.066
So part of this is when you look back and you do the studies, unsurprisingly,

1316
01:15:20.106 --> 01:15:23.686
the aged mice, they don't respond as well to mutant KRAS vaccination.

1317
01:15:23.886 --> 01:15:27.626
This is what we see in terms of flu vaccines and other vaccines that we use in

1318
01:15:27.686 --> 01:15:31.466
an infectious disease context. But looking at

1319
01:15:31.546 --> 01:15:35.226
after immunization KRAS G12D peptide stimulation in an interferon

1320
01:15:35.306 --> 01:15:38.606
gamma ELISpot, it's diminished in aged mice.

1321
01:15:39.386 --> 01:15:42.586
If you then neutralize GDF15 in these aged mice, you see that you get an

1322
01:15:42.626 --> 01:15:45.446
improvement in the generation of neoantigen T cells.

1323
01:15:46.106 --> 01:15:49.575
So again, this is something that we think that maybe is doing both the activity,

1324
01:15:49.646 --> 01:15:53.226
but also now maybe priming is an improved function here.

1325
01:15:54.026 --> 01:15:55.906
But we wanted to take a look at our human data.

1326
01:15:56.026 --> 01:15:59.896
So this is a prior trial of a cancer vaccine called GVAX,

1327
01:15:59.966 --> 01:16:02.726
which is not a mutant KRAS vaccine, but a different one.

1328
01:16:02.795 --> 01:16:06.686
And we looked at the expression of GDF15 in patients on this

1329
01:16:06.726 --> 01:16:07.015
trial.

1330
01:16:07.906 --> 01:16:10.666
The older patients had higher GDF15, as we'd expect.

1331
01:16:10.846 --> 01:16:14.226
But if you look at high versus low GDF15 levels, the patients with the highest

1332
01:16:14.366 --> 01:16:17.706
GDF15 had the worst overall survival in this cohort.

1333
01:16:18.186 --> 01:16:20.806
And this was even controlling for age as a continuous variable.

1334
01:16:20.906 --> 01:16:24.186
So here, the hazard ratio for high versus low is about two,

1335
01:16:24.826 --> 01:16:28.606
not a good thing. But if you account for age just to see if it's higher in the age,

1336
01:16:28.666 --> 01:16:32.496
maybe it's the older patients doing worse, it drops to 1.99,

1337
01:16:32.846 --> 01:16:36.646
telling me that most of this bad effect is probably from the high GDF15 in our

1338
01:16:36.706 --> 01:16:37.646
statistical models.

1339
01:16:38.826 --> 01:16:40.346
So we wanted to say, what can we do about this?

1340
01:16:40.526 --> 01:16:42.026
I'm telling you, I think this is important.

1341
01:16:42.546 --> 01:16:44.936
Maybe it's influencing therapy responses.

1342
01:16:45.406 --> 01:16:48.606
Why don't we try this in the aged mouse models where we neutralize

1343
01:16:48.666 --> 01:16:52.566
GDF15, but also give checkpoint inhibitor and vaccine as

1344
01:16:52.606 --> 01:16:53.866
it's currently given in the clinic?

1345
01:16:54.726 --> 01:16:57.986
And there's a lot of groups here, but I think just to walk through it briefly,

1346
01:16:58.446 --> 01:17:02.126
the GDF15 neutralized cohort, you have the

1347
01:17:02.166 --> 01:17:03.966
reduction in tumor size we've shown here.

1348
01:17:04.726 --> 01:17:08.486
Dual ICI in this model is somewhat effective, but you never get long-term

1349
01:17:08.566 --> 01:17:09.226
tumor control.

1350
01:17:10.066 --> 01:17:13.866
If you combine just ICIs and GDF15 neutralization, you actually don't get

1351
01:17:13.926 --> 01:17:17.706
major changes in tumor size. If you add ICIs

1352
01:17:17.786 --> 01:17:21.026
and vaccine together, again, it's not different than just ICIs alone.

1353
01:17:21.566 --> 01:17:25.226
But when you give all three together, we get the smallest tumors, a significant

1354
01:17:25.276 --> 01:17:28.186
reduction in tumor size. And actually, two of the

1355
01:17:29.266 --> 01:17:31.026
seven tumors here are completely gone.

1356
01:17:31.106 --> 01:17:33.646
If you look at the tissue, this is actually just normal pancreas.

1357
01:17:34.446 --> 01:17:37.246
And I think something else was interesting, if you then look at this in a

1358
01:17:37.266 --> 01:17:40.806
therapeutic context, we're also seeing an increase in neoantigen-specific T

1359
01:17:40.826 --> 01:17:44.726
cells after the addition of neutralization of GDF15 to cancer

1360
01:17:44.746 --> 01:17:46.906
vaccination and dual checkpoint inhibition.

1361
01:17:47.486 --> 01:17:50.686
So something we're really interested in pursuing in a platform study where we're

1362
01:17:50.726 --> 01:17:54.656
looking at this in patients, but again, hopefully an illustration of age inform

1363
01:17:54.656 --> 01:17:58.386
modeling making a difference in what we're seeing in terms of therapy responses.

1364
01:17:59.426 --> 01:18:03.136
So with that, I just wanted to leave with some of the similar points where we think

1365
01:18:03.166 --> 01:18:06.866
that biological aging is a key factor that influences the PDAC TME

1366
01:18:07.346 --> 01:18:09.646
and can really be important for these therapy responses.

1367
01:18:10.186 --> 01:18:13.506
And I think considering use of age inform models is likely going to be very

1368
01:18:13.546 --> 01:18:16.746
important in developing rational therapy

1369
01:18:17.086 --> 01:18:19.286
combinations that can improve outcomes for people.

1370
01:18:20.026 --> 01:18:23.566
And I think, again, we're going to need a lot of these combinations to join that

1371
01:18:23.626 --> 01:18:27.495
immunotherapy revolution because we're up against a very tough environment, and

1372
01:18:27.906 --> 01:18:30.766
anything we can do to move the needle for patients with pancreas cancer is

1373
01:18:30.966 --> 01:18:32.065
something that we'd love to do.

1374
01:18:32.946 --> 01:18:35.736
And with that, I want to thank everyone that works with me in the lab and

1375
01:18:36.446 --> 01:18:39.946
collaborates with me at Hopkins and beyond, and thank the patients that have

1376
01:18:39.966 --> 01:18:43.406
participated in these studies and the funders for the work.

1377
01:18:43.446 --> 01:18:44.986
Thank you.

1378
01:18:53.266 --> 01:18:56.686
Great presentation. Congrats on a very complete and thorough story.

1379
01:18:56.716 --> 01:18:57.526
I just was wondering,

1380
01:19:00.326 --> 01:19:03.086
to what extent do you think there might be some involvement of

1381
01:19:03.626 --> 01:19:04.546
macrophages?

1382
01:19:05.446 --> 01:19:09.146
Even the T cells later on weren't really participating

1383
01:19:09.486 --> 01:19:13.006
in the microenvironment and being any kind of apparent role and

1384
01:19:13.686 --> 01:19:17.286
the known effect of GDF15 with the

1385
01:19:17.326 --> 01:19:20.206
macrophages. Do you think there could be some kind of link there as well?

1386
01:19:20.246 --> 01:19:22.446
Have you tried to deplete macrophages or anything like that?

1387
01:19:22.506 --> 01:19:26.296
I think there could be. As you've mentioned, it's also known to have effects on

1388
01:19:26.306 --> 01:19:28.146
macrophage function and activity.

1389
01:19:28.246 --> 01:19:31.686
So I think what we've seen in terms of abundance levels

1390
01:19:31.746 --> 01:19:35.326
and crude metrics of macrophage function, just

1391
01:19:35.426 --> 01:19:39.380
206, 163, for instance, has notShowing a major trend here after

1392
01:19:39.450 --> 01:19:40.870
neutralization or in the young in age.

1393
01:19:40.970 --> 01:19:44.690
But we're waiting on some more detailed CyTOF and IMC

1394
01:19:44.770 --> 01:19:48.710
data to really delve into that, because I do think they're likely contributing.

1395
01:19:48.770 --> 01:19:51.130
We just haven't captured it yet with our analyses.

1396
01:19:53.170 --> 01:19:55.330
So really nice presentation.

1397
01:19:56.510 --> 01:20:00.460
Question about the GDF15. There's now

1398
01:20:00.530 --> 01:20:03.900
efforts looking at combined GLP1,

1399
01:20:04.150 --> 01:20:07.930
GDF15 agonists to treat obesity.

1400
01:20:07.990 --> 01:20:08.090
Yeah.

1401
01:20:08.150 --> 01:20:11.910
Which sounds, based on your data, a bit concerning.

1402
01:20:12.450 --> 01:20:12.950
Your thoughts?

1403
01:20:14.030 --> 01:20:17.890
Yeah. I think this is one of those things of risk

1404
01:20:18.090 --> 01:20:19.790
in human disease, right? I

1405
01:20:20.930 --> 01:20:24.630
would say if you have pancreas cancer, I'd be very concerned about it based on

1406
01:20:24.970 --> 01:20:25.750
these data. But,

1407
01:20:27.510 --> 01:20:31.110
if it helps someone not have a heart attack at 50, that's a different calculus

1408
01:20:31.150 --> 01:20:32.890
compared to the overall risk of pancreas cancer.

1409
01:20:32.950 --> 01:20:36.590
I think it could be harmful, but looking at it at a

1410
01:20:36.630 --> 01:20:39.350
population level is probably where you have to draw the line.

1411
01:20:39.630 --> 01:20:43.350
I haven't had any data in this model showing that it

1412
01:20:43.390 --> 01:20:47.170
increases initiation or transformation of cells to kind of push

1413
01:20:47.210 --> 01:20:50.970
towards that initial step in oncogenesis, but rather in a kind of an

1414
01:20:50.990 --> 01:20:54.970
established cell model promotes further escape.

1415
01:20:55.570 --> 01:20:57.130
I think we need to know more, but

1416
01:20:58.150 --> 01:20:58.250
yeah.

1417
01:20:58.380 --> 01:21:01.990
So there's not a general role for GDF15

1418
01:21:02.690 --> 01:21:04.950
in aging immune function?

1419
01:21:06.230 --> 01:21:09.590
I think it's still being unraveled, but

1420
01:21:10.550 --> 01:21:12.830
your point is a good one and something we've got to be careful about when we're

1421
01:21:12.870 --> 01:21:13.570
doing these studies.

1422
01:21:14.050 --> 01:21:14.310
Thank you.

1423
01:21:14.710 --> 01:21:15.010
Thank you.

1424
01:21:16.070 --> 01:21:19.710
Hi. My question is very maybe related to the previous

1425
01:21:19.990 --> 01:21:23.090
question, but if I remember correctly,

1426
01:21:23.330 --> 01:21:27.010
GDF15 level is known to be inversely

1427
01:21:27.070 --> 01:21:29.230
correlated with mitochondrial function.

1428
01:21:29.830 --> 01:21:31.010
So my question is,

1429
01:21:31.830 --> 01:21:35.630
have you checked whether your observation is mainly

1430
01:21:35.670 --> 01:21:39.460
because mitochondrial function in T cell reducing

1431
01:21:39.650 --> 01:21:40.210
old mice?

1432
01:21:41.290 --> 01:21:42.590
No, I haven't checked that specifically.

1433
01:21:42.610 --> 01:21:45.870
I think it's a great thought and something we can definitely do.

1434
01:21:45.910 --> 01:21:46.630
Thanks for the suggestion.

1435
01:21:48.710 --> 01:21:49.030
Thank you all.

1436
01:21:57.290 --> 01:22:00.870
Thank you, Daniel, for a great talk, and congratulations again on your

1437
01:22:00.930 --> 01:22:02.610
NextGen Star Award.

1438
01:22:04.270 --> 01:22:08.210
So for those who still have a little bit of energy left on this

1439
01:22:08.230 --> 01:22:09.010
Tuesday afternoon,

1440
01:22:10.090 --> 01:22:13.510
the last talk will really focus on work in my lab, and we're going to switch a

1441
01:22:13.550 --> 01:22:16.750
little bit gears to go more into the molecular links

1442
01:22:17.450 --> 01:22:19.760
between aging, inflammation, and cancer.

1443
01:22:21.150 --> 01:22:25.030
So these are my disclosures. And our lab looks at this through the lens

1444
01:22:25.150 --> 01:22:28.600
of gene expression regulation for a process called RNA splicing,

1445
01:22:29.470 --> 01:22:33.450
which really enables each one of your favorite gene to generate multiple

1446
01:22:33.530 --> 01:22:37.079
RNA and potentially protein isoforms, some of which can have

1447
01:22:37.110 --> 01:22:38.090
distinct function.

1448
01:22:39.250 --> 01:22:42.910
And we've known for quite a while that tumors and normal

1449
01:22:42.950 --> 01:22:46.370
tissues have quite a different set of isoforms.

1450
01:22:46.850 --> 01:22:50.670
Those isoforms impact many genes that are associated with cancer hallmarks.

1451
01:22:50.750 --> 01:22:53.430
They can help cells proliferate faster, evade more,

1452
01:22:54.690 --> 01:22:58.510
escape apoptosis, stimulate metabolism, or

1453
01:22:58.590 --> 01:23:02.090
even impact immune responses. We've come to appreciate in the

1454
01:23:02.130 --> 01:23:05.830
last 10 to 15 years that many of those genes that are

1455
01:23:05.890 --> 01:23:09.690
abnormally spliced in tumors are actually not necessarily

1456
01:23:09.750 --> 01:23:13.720
mutated, but they are the consequence of a dysregulation

1457
01:23:13.790 --> 01:23:17.750
of the splicing machinery. Which is itself either mutated or

1458
01:23:17.830 --> 01:23:21.490
undergoes epigenetic or transcriptional, post-transcriptional

1459
01:23:21.550 --> 01:23:25.110
changes. The reason we're really focusing on RNA

1460
01:23:25.190 --> 01:23:29.150
splicing is that because at the end of the day, it's

1461
01:23:29.190 --> 01:23:32.890
really the readout of all the other molecular processes happening

1462
01:23:32.970 --> 01:23:36.240
upstream. So your accumulation of DNA mutation,

1463
01:23:36.390 --> 01:23:39.890
epigenetic changes, transcriptional regulation, all of this

1464
01:23:40.210 --> 01:23:43.930
converges really on RNA splicing, which is the last steps we can

1465
01:23:44.150 --> 01:23:47.550
really measure accurately in high throughput manners.

1466
01:23:49.870 --> 01:23:53.810
We're also really focusing on RNA splicing because it represents

1467
01:23:54.170 --> 01:23:58.019
still an untapped reservoir of novel therapeutic opportunity for

1468
01:23:58.030 --> 01:24:01.810
cancer that can, either targeting those novel

1469
01:24:02.250 --> 01:24:05.690
mis-spliced isoform, exploiting some of the splicing

1470
01:24:05.770 --> 01:24:09.510
vulnerability by targeting the splicing machinery, but also

1471
01:24:09.550 --> 01:24:13.490
weaponizing some of the splicing-derived novel peptides, which can

1472
01:24:13.530 --> 01:24:17.000
really constitute novel sources for immunotherapies.

1473
01:24:19.050 --> 01:24:22.470
So my lab over the years have mapped those splicing

1474
01:24:22.510 --> 01:24:25.730
vulnerability across multiple tumor types

1475
01:24:25.810 --> 01:24:29.730
using large cohorts of patient primary

1476
01:24:29.810 --> 01:24:33.550
samples and leveraging sequencing approaches, including

1477
01:24:33.610 --> 01:24:36.810
short-read RNA sequencing in the context, for example, of

1478
01:24:36.870 --> 01:24:40.670
MYC-dependent tumors, including breast cancer, as well as

1479
01:24:41.030 --> 01:24:43.650
brain cancers and other tumor types such as gastric.

1480
01:24:44.630 --> 01:24:48.570
We've really over the past five years came to embrace a new

1481
01:24:48.610 --> 01:24:51.870
technology called long-read RNA sequencing.

1482
01:24:52.450 --> 01:24:56.210
That is particularly well-suited for the discovery of these novel junctions

1483
01:24:56.310 --> 01:24:59.790
and potentially novel neoantigens and novel protein coding

1484
01:24:59.910 --> 01:25:03.790
isoforms, which really enables you to read each of the

1485
01:25:03.850 --> 01:25:07.710
isoforms from beginning to end without having to reassemble

1486
01:25:07.719 --> 01:25:09.350
those from short reads. Which

1487
01:25:10.530 --> 01:25:13.630
is very powerful, but also can be sometimes misleading.

1488
01:25:14.130 --> 01:25:17.980
And so we've applied this approach to so far two tumor

1489
01:25:18.030 --> 01:25:21.730
types: breast cancer, which is published, and I invite you to look at the paper, as

1490
01:25:21.750 --> 01:25:22.680
well as lung cancer.

1491
01:25:23.570 --> 01:25:27.330
And in both, we really showed that half of the isoforms that we detect with

1492
01:25:27.430 --> 01:25:31.050
long reads in primary patient tumors are absent from

1493
01:25:31.110 --> 01:25:34.770
reference transcriptomes. They're not even annotated in gene code databases.

1494
01:25:35.510 --> 01:25:39.410
And of those, at least half are predicted to encode novel

1495
01:25:39.590 --> 01:25:42.030
protein coding isoforms and generate novel

1496
01:25:42.870 --> 01:25:46.510
peptides. Including, for example, in our lung cancer study, we

1497
01:25:46.550 --> 01:25:50.310
identified a novel isoform that is important for immune signaling in

1498
01:25:50.410 --> 01:25:53.990
STAT2 molecules that really predicts responses to

1499
01:25:54.010 --> 01:25:55.530
immunotherapy in lung cancer

1500
01:25:55.650 --> 01:25:59.540
patientsSo as I mentioned, many of those novel

1501
01:25:59.600 --> 01:26:03.060
isoforms are caused by dysregulation of the splicing machinery.

1502
01:26:03.760 --> 01:26:07.440
Notably, in many of hematological malignancy, we see

1503
01:26:08.080 --> 01:26:12.020
the appearance of age-related mutation in

1504
01:26:12.440 --> 01:26:14.540
many splicing factors that are

1505
01:26:15.700 --> 01:26:19.450
gaining novel functions and enabling to detect novel splice site.

1506
01:26:20.280 --> 01:26:24.180
On the other hand, in solid tumors, we see a lot of expression changes in the

1507
01:26:24.200 --> 01:26:27.780
splicing machinery, which again regulates hundreds of downstream

1508
01:26:27.840 --> 01:26:31.780
isoforms. And so a lot of the work in the lab over the past

1509
01:26:31.820 --> 01:26:35.420
10 years has been focused on really understanding what are the consequences of

1510
01:26:35.460 --> 01:26:38.680
those changes and what is triggering

1511
01:26:38.980 --> 01:26:40.900
those changes in splicing factors.

1512
01:26:41.920 --> 01:26:45.390
And so the one process that we've came to study, and that's why

1513
01:26:45.400 --> 01:26:49.220
I'm here talking today, is really how aging itself

1514
01:26:49.280 --> 01:26:52.760
impacts the reprogramming of both the transcriptional,

1515
01:26:52.900 --> 01:26:55.780
epigenetic, and post-transcriptional repertoire.

1516
01:26:56.700 --> 01:26:56.760
And

1517
01:26:57.800 --> 01:27:01.619
following on Sandy's very elegant talk, our question was what really

1518
01:27:01.660 --> 01:27:05.080
happens early on before the tumors develop in the

1519
01:27:05.120 --> 01:27:07.240
context of breast cancer?

1520
01:27:08.140 --> 01:27:11.680
As you heard, breast cancer is really an age-related

1521
01:27:11.720 --> 01:27:12.220
disease,

1522
01:27:13.540 --> 01:27:17.360
and we know that changes in splicing also appear

1523
01:27:18.460 --> 01:27:22.240
with aging, especially in the context of brain and neurodegenerative diseases.

1524
01:27:22.660 --> 01:27:26.160
But when we started the studies, really very little was known about what happens in

1525
01:27:26.180 --> 01:27:28.160
breast tissue with aging.

1526
01:27:29.280 --> 01:27:32.680
And so our initial hypothesis was that we know the tumors

1527
01:27:32.720 --> 01:27:36.360
accumulate a number of alterations and level of isoforms and

1528
01:27:36.420 --> 01:27:39.700
splicing factors, but we don't really know how early this happens.

1529
01:27:39.830 --> 01:27:43.100
And so we hypothesized that with age and chronic inflammation,

1530
01:27:43.920 --> 01:27:47.460
there is a reprogramming of the splicing repertoire, which will enable the

1531
01:27:47.500 --> 01:27:51.240
cells to be in a more pro-tumorigenic environment.

1532
01:27:51.750 --> 01:27:54.660
And so Brittany Angarola, who was a postdoc in my lab at the time,

1533
01:27:55.460 --> 01:27:57.040
very bravely tackled this question.

1534
01:27:57.460 --> 01:28:01.160
And so we started by using mice, where you can have really genetically

1535
01:28:01.220 --> 01:28:04.600
identical animals that really differ only by age.

1536
01:28:05.060 --> 01:28:08.560
So we're using either mature adult animals, three to six months old, or

1537
01:28:08.720 --> 01:28:11.320
elderly animals, which are 18 to 24 months.

1538
01:28:12.340 --> 01:28:15.740
And we also leverage a large collection of human mammary

1539
01:28:15.780 --> 01:28:19.480
epithelial cells collected by Marc Labarge of City of Hope from various

1540
01:28:19.550 --> 01:28:23.300
healthy donor at different ages. So we started with mice to really

1541
01:28:23.320 --> 01:28:26.600
convince ourselves that age itself is sufficient to trigger splicing

1542
01:28:26.640 --> 01:28:30.380
changes. Here we isolated specifically from the mammary gland

1543
01:28:30.560 --> 01:28:34.470
two epithelial cell populations, the luminal epithelial cells,

1544
01:28:34.540 --> 01:28:38.440
which are thought to be the origin of most breast cancer, as well as

1545
01:28:38.480 --> 01:28:42.320
the myoepithelial cells, which are still epithelial but are more fibroblast-like

1546
01:28:42.760 --> 01:28:45.540
and really form a barrier that is supposed to

1547
01:28:45.860 --> 01:28:49.280
protect invasion and metastatic

1548
01:28:49.380 --> 01:28:52.720
dissemination. We isolated those, and then we performed

1549
01:28:53.600 --> 01:28:57.440
very deep RNA sequencing and long-read RNA sequencing to

1550
01:28:57.480 --> 01:29:00.620
identify changes in splicing between young and old animals.

1551
01:29:01.860 --> 01:29:05.570
And so, to our delight, we identified that age alone is

1552
01:29:05.600 --> 01:29:09.180
sufficient to trigger robust splicing changes in both

1553
01:29:09.380 --> 01:29:13.080
epithelial cell populations, with the majority of those being

1554
01:29:13.120 --> 01:29:16.140
cassette exon events or an exon that can be included or skipped.

1555
01:29:16.720 --> 01:29:20.500
To our surprise, 90% of those changes were really cell type

1556
01:29:20.620 --> 01:29:23.880
specific. So the changes in the luminal compartment and

1557
01:29:23.920 --> 01:29:26.760
myoepithelial compartment are really quite different.

1558
01:29:28.640 --> 01:29:32.270
Having convinced ourselves that age itself is sufficient to trigger those

1559
01:29:32.340 --> 01:29:34.640
changes, we then wanted to see what happens in women.

1560
01:29:34.690 --> 01:29:38.160
And so here we collaborated with Marc Labarge from City of Hope, who

1561
01:29:38.200 --> 01:29:42.180
collected luminal and myoepithelial cells from healthy women with no familiar

1562
01:29:42.240 --> 01:29:44.700
history of breast cancer, no BRCA mutation.

1563
01:29:44.720 --> 01:29:48.120
And again, we performed very deep RNA sequencing and long-read sequencing.

1564
01:29:48.740 --> 01:29:52.700
And here again, despite of course having very different genetic backgrounds, we

1565
01:29:52.740 --> 01:29:55.960
identified robust and reproducible splicing

1566
01:29:56.460 --> 01:29:59.240
changes in both luminal and myoepithelial

1567
01:29:59.280 --> 01:30:02.940
cells between cells from older versus

1568
01:30:03.040 --> 01:30:03.700
younger women.

1569
01:30:04.580 --> 01:30:08.520
Again, 90% of those changes were cell type specific, and we

1570
01:30:08.540 --> 01:30:12.380
would have absolutely not been able to capture them if we just looked at the entire

1571
01:30:12.420 --> 01:30:15.999
tissue. Very encouragingly, a subset of the gene that are spliced

1572
01:30:16.360 --> 01:30:19.920
are shared between mouse and humans, suggesting that there are some aspects of

1573
01:30:19.940 --> 01:30:22.960
aging of breast that can be modeled in mice.

1574
01:30:24.960 --> 01:30:28.820
We then looked really at what can we gain from doing those long-read sequencing

1575
01:30:28.860 --> 01:30:30.560
approaches. As I mentioned in tumors,

1576
01:30:31.560 --> 01:30:35.310
which have, of course, a lot of mutations and epigenetic changes,

1577
01:30:35.660 --> 01:30:39.040
we see a lot of novel isoforms. What about in normal healthy tissue?

1578
01:30:39.560 --> 01:30:41.880
And so here again to our surprise, even with

1579
01:30:42.300 --> 01:30:45.760
histologically healthy tissues

1580
01:30:46.300 --> 01:30:49.640
in those luminal cells, a third of the isoforms we

1581
01:30:49.680 --> 01:30:53.320
identify with long-read sequencing approaches are completely novel.

1582
01:30:53.360 --> 01:30:56.580
They're not present in any of the current reference catalog,

1583
01:30:57.000 --> 01:31:00.400
suggesting, again, a really very deep reprogramming of the splicing

1584
01:31:00.480 --> 01:31:04.340
repertoire with age. So what are the genes that are

1585
01:31:04.400 --> 01:31:08.370
affected by splicing? Interestingly, the top category of genes

1586
01:31:08.380 --> 01:31:11.770
that were spliced with age were associated with DNA repair genes,

1587
01:31:12.320 --> 01:31:15.020
and so we're currently investigating a number of those.

1588
01:31:15.300 --> 01:31:18.880
Our two working hypothesis that are that either with

1589
01:31:19.100 --> 01:31:23.020
age, those DNA repair gene isoforms actually make the

1590
01:31:23.060 --> 01:31:25.080
machinery more efficient at repairing

1591
01:31:26.680 --> 01:31:30.440
damages and actually preventing aging or, on the other hand,

1592
01:31:30.500 --> 01:31:32.960
that this is associated with the decline

1593
01:31:33.020 --> 01:31:36.980
we see with fitness and the

1594
01:31:37.040 --> 01:31:40.460
accumulation of mutation. And so stay tuned for our

1595
01:31:40.580 --> 01:31:41.080
findings.

1596
01:31:42.660 --> 01:31:46.640
We then asked the question, are those changes actually relevant to

1597
01:31:46.720 --> 01:31:48.900
anything we see in human breast tumors?

1598
01:31:48.960 --> 01:31:52.820
So here we focus on luminal A and B breast cancer subtypes,

1599
01:31:53.420 --> 01:31:55.920
which really represent the majority of

1600
01:31:56.900 --> 01:32:00.810
breast cancers in older women. And we identify that

1601
01:32:00.880 --> 01:32:04.364
of thissplicing events we see in older luminal

1602
01:32:04.484 --> 01:32:08.304
cells. There is a subset of 219 that we also see

1603
01:32:08.364 --> 01:32:12.264
in older breast tumors, suggesting that the cells that gave rise to

1604
01:32:12.324 --> 01:32:15.364
this tumor already had this age-related alteration.

1605
01:32:16.424 --> 01:32:18.804
So how are those alterations triggered?

1606
01:32:19.404 --> 01:32:22.864
We think that at least in part, this is due to changes in splicing factor

1607
01:32:22.884 --> 01:32:26.684
expression. In older luminal cell, we see decreased

1608
01:32:26.724 --> 01:32:30.624
expression of a splicing factor called quaking, and we also see that

1609
01:32:30.684 --> 01:32:33.724
in breast tumors across the entire Cancer Genome Atlas projects,

1610
01:32:34.804 --> 01:32:38.744
almost half of the tumors have a decreased expression of quaking, which may in

1611
01:32:38.804 --> 01:32:40.964
part explain some of the splicing changes.

1612
01:32:42.713 --> 01:32:44.044
So in summary for this part,

1613
01:32:44.844 --> 01:32:48.564
I hope you'll remember that aging really triggers not

1614
01:32:48.624 --> 01:32:52.484
only accumulation of mutations, epigenetic changes, but also

1615
01:32:52.524 --> 01:32:56.184
downstream impacts the expression of RNA isoforms,

1616
01:32:56.604 --> 01:32:59.564
as well as the regulation of those isoform at the splicing level.

1617
01:33:00.044 --> 01:33:03.444
We see a really striking similarities between aging and cancer.

1618
01:33:04.684 --> 01:33:07.764
And there are a number of remaining questions, really.

1619
01:33:08.024 --> 01:33:11.784
How is this regulating? How does this connect to other cancer hallmarks, including

1620
01:33:11.824 --> 01:33:12.464
epigenetic?

1621
01:33:13.444 --> 01:33:16.904
How are those splicing changes regulated, and what are their functional

1622
01:33:16.944 --> 01:33:20.664
consequences? And of course, what happens in other cell

1623
01:33:20.764 --> 01:33:24.644
types? As you've heard, the epithelial cells are really critical for

1624
01:33:24.784 --> 01:33:28.584
transformation of solid tumors, but of course, they live in an environment

1625
01:33:28.664 --> 01:33:32.274
of stromal and immune cells, which are equally important.

1626
01:33:32.714 --> 01:33:34.434
And so to start addressing this question,

1627
01:33:36.004 --> 01:33:39.314
in a paper published last year, we profiled

1628
01:33:40.124 --> 01:33:42.944
both the transcriptome and epigenome of mammary

1629
01:33:43.764 --> 01:33:47.374
cell types within the mammary glands of older and younger mice,

1630
01:33:48.244 --> 01:33:50.864
as well as done spatial transcriptomics.

1631
01:33:51.574 --> 01:33:55.474
And just to quickly summarize our findings, our atlas, which we hope will

1632
01:33:55.504 --> 01:33:59.424
be useful to other researchers, uncovered that with age, we

1633
01:33:59.584 --> 01:34:03.284
see in the mammary gland, we see changes in cell proportional, changes in gene

1634
01:34:03.324 --> 01:34:06.584
expression, as well as changes in chromatin accessibility

1635
01:34:07.064 --> 01:34:10.644
across all different cell type compartments, both the epithelial cells, stromal

1636
01:34:10.724 --> 01:34:11.904
cells and immune cells.

1637
01:34:12.924 --> 01:34:16.684
Strikingly, across all compartment, we've seen increased cell plasticity

1638
01:34:17.184 --> 01:34:21.164
and loss of cell identity. So the epithelial cells become less

1639
01:34:21.184 --> 01:34:24.944
epithelial. The luminal and myoepithelial start merging together.

1640
01:34:25.004 --> 01:34:28.694
We see increased expression of genes with tumor suppressor activity and

1641
01:34:28.724 --> 01:34:31.264
increased expression of pro-inflammatory molecules.

1642
01:34:31.844 --> 01:34:35.764
So if you're interested to look more into this, we invite you to look in

1643
01:34:35.824 --> 01:34:39.224
the paper. And so for the sake of time, I'll just give you two examples of

1644
01:34:39.244 --> 01:34:42.944
really very exciting behaviors we identified.

1645
01:34:43.504 --> 01:34:47.244
So in the stromal compartment, we see changes in the number

1646
01:34:47.324 --> 01:34:50.464
of fibroblasts with age, but also in the types of fibroblasts.

1647
01:34:50.504 --> 01:34:54.464
For example, this fibroblast C2 population here in yellow really

1648
01:34:54.524 --> 01:34:58.184
increases in magnitude in aged animals.

1649
01:34:58.664 --> 01:35:01.204
Those actually start expressing

1650
01:35:02.784 --> 01:35:05.504
different cell markers. They become less fibroblast-like.

1651
01:35:05.564 --> 01:35:09.284
They lose some of the fibronectin expression and gain some of the

1652
01:35:09.344 --> 01:35:13.204
collagen expression. They also start expressing some pro-inflammatory

1653
01:35:13.244 --> 01:35:16.144
molecules, and they may be more adipocyte-like.

1654
01:35:17.144 --> 01:35:20.964
And finally, they also start become expressing more of the

1655
01:35:21.004 --> 01:35:24.824
senescence markers, which is similar to what has been described in other

1656
01:35:24.884 --> 01:35:25.664
tissue types.

1657
01:35:27.964 --> 01:35:31.804
In the immune compartment, we see, of course, a very dramatic

1658
01:35:31.864 --> 01:35:35.584
remodeling of the immune landscape of a decrease in naive CD4 and

1659
01:35:35.644 --> 01:35:36.384
CD8 cells,

1660
01:35:37.204 --> 01:35:41.144
as well as an increase in the numbers of granzyme K positive cells, gamma

1661
01:35:41.184 --> 01:35:45.104
delta MAIT cells, and memory CD4 and NK

1662
01:35:45.144 --> 01:35:48.994
cells. The largest population that increases with age in the mammary gland are

1663
01:35:48.994 --> 01:35:52.824
really those granzyme K positive cells, which have also been

1664
01:35:54.744 --> 01:35:58.504
seen in other tissues of age, those tissue resident

1665
01:35:58.564 --> 01:36:02.474
cells. They express markers of inflammation,

1666
01:36:02.584 --> 01:36:06.184
pro-inflammatory molecules, as well as some

1667
01:36:08.124 --> 01:36:11.924
cytokines such as CCL5, which I think Sandy also saw in some of

1668
01:36:11.984 --> 01:36:12.124
her

1669
01:36:14.204 --> 01:36:17.844
models, and really suggesting a very important

1670
01:36:18.304 --> 01:36:20.143
remodeling of the immune compartment.

1671
01:36:21.764 --> 01:36:25.564
Finally, we use spatial transcriptomic to really confirm the presence of the

1672
01:36:25.824 --> 01:36:28.744
tissue-resident immune cells. So here we profiled using

1673
01:36:29.604 --> 01:36:33.324
the Visium platform, mammary glands from young and old animals

1674
01:36:33.804 --> 01:36:36.664
identifying multiple cell populations.

1675
01:36:37.284 --> 01:36:40.664
And very excitingly, we were able to confirm

1676
01:36:41.084 --> 01:36:44.164
that those granzyme K positive cells, but also

1677
01:36:45.384 --> 01:36:46.104
some of the other

1678
01:36:46.904 --> 01:36:50.624
gamma delta T cells and PDCD1 positive cells, are

1679
01:36:50.744 --> 01:36:54.434
really enriched in the tissue, and they're enriched in

1680
01:36:54.564 --> 01:36:58.494
